00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:24.920
PROFESSOR: OK let's get started.

00:00:27.790 --> 00:00:31.480
I once taught with
a professor who

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:36.100
was lamenting the fact that as
the term progresses attendance

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:37.830
in lecture tends to drop off.

00:00:37.830 --> 00:00:40.640
And gets pretty dramatic
by the end of the term

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:43.760
when you're lecturing,
and nobody's there.

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:45.980
And I asked him what
he did about it.

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:48.180
And he thought about
it and he said,

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:51.030
there's only two things that
can get students to come

00:00:51.030 --> 00:00:55.840
to lecture, candy and sex.

00:00:55.840 --> 00:01:01.510
Now we've already tried
candy, so today we're

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:04.410
going to talk about sex.

00:01:04.410 --> 00:01:07.600
In fact we're going
to use graph theory

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:10.630
to address a decades
old debate concerning

00:01:10.630 --> 00:01:15.240
the relative promiscuity
of men versus women.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:19.410
Now graphs are incredibly useful
structures in computer science,

00:01:19.410 --> 00:01:22.270
and we're going to be studying
them for the next five or six

00:01:22.270 --> 00:01:23.520
lectures.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:27.800
They come up in all sorts
of applications, scheduling,

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:31.070
optimization,
communications, the design

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:32.710
and analysis of algorithms.

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:35.310
In fact next week, you're
going to see how to Stanford

00:01:35.310 --> 00:01:38.990
graduate students
became gazillionaires

00:01:38.990 --> 00:01:43.200
because they use graph
theoretic in a clever way.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:46.470
But let's talk about sex.

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:48.640
The issue that we're
going to address today

00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:52.660
is one of the most talked
about, and most well studied,

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:55.900
questions in all
of human sociology.

00:01:55.900 --> 00:02:00.400
On average, who has more
opposite gender partners,

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:02.715
men or women?

00:02:02.715 --> 00:02:05.310
Now opposite gender is
going to be important.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:09.035
And by this I mean,
one boy, and one girl.

00:02:09.035 --> 00:02:11.035
All right, I'm not making
a political statement.

00:02:11.035 --> 00:02:16.770
It's just that the math is a lot
easier that way, as you'll see.

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.860
Now I'd like to start
by taking a pole here

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:21.270
to see what you
think about that.

00:02:21.270 --> 00:02:24.830
So raise your and if you
think men, on average,

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:27.910
have more opposite gender
partners than women do.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:31.095
Only a few.

00:02:31.095 --> 00:02:33.401
AUDIENCE: In life or [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:33.401 --> 00:02:34.400
PROFESSOR: Um, you can--

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:39.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:40.640
PROFESSOR: One on one.

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:43.970
OK, so let's say over the course
of their lives, let's say,

00:02:43.970 --> 00:02:48.200
or over the course of
2010, that men in America

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:51.460
have more opposite-gender
partners than women in America,

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:52.830
say in 2010.

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:55.030
Raise your hand if you think
men have more going on.

00:02:55.030 --> 00:02:57.040
All right a bunch of you.

00:02:57.040 --> 00:02:58.730
Raise your hand if
you think women have

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:00.890
more opposite-gender partners?

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:02.490
This is unusual.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:04.870
Maybe even more voted for
women, but it's close.

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:07.744
Raise your hand if
you think it's equal.

00:03:07.744 --> 00:03:09.680
All right, about the same.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:12.550
Raise your hand if you think
there's no way to know,

00:03:12.550 --> 00:03:15.210
that it's hopeless to
really figure it out.

00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:17.210
All right, nobody goes for that.

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:18.565
All right, good.

00:03:18.565 --> 00:03:20.460
All right well now in
the popular literature,

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:23.620
I think the feelings are
different than expressed here.

00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:25.450
Pretty much universally,
in the literature,

00:03:25.450 --> 00:03:28.000
it's believed that men have
more opposite-gender partners

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.216
than women.

00:03:29.216 --> 00:03:30.590
And in fact, you
could even think

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:33.120
about that, if you
think about literature,

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:35.780
the leader of the
harem is always a man.

00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:37.680
And he's got lots of women.

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:40.540
In polygamist
cultures, it's always

00:03:40.540 --> 00:03:44.890
the man that has multiple
wives, not the reverse.

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:47.410
Now not surprisingly,
this issue has

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:49.620
been studied
"scientifically," I'll

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:54.520
put in quotes, extensively, in
one of the largest studies ever

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:56.220
done.

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:58.210
Researchers from
University of Chicago

00:03:58.210 --> 00:04:03.200
interviewed 2,500 people, at
random, over several years.

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:05.800
They brought them in,
on many occasions,

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:08.920
to try to get the answer for
the question once and for all.

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:11.560
And they wrote
this 700 page book,

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:14.680
called The soul of Social
Organization of Sexuality:

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:18.050
Sexual Practices in the US.

00:04:18.050 --> 00:04:19.670
Actually walking
around with this book

00:04:19.670 --> 00:04:22.720
has proved to be a
little embarrassing.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:25.890
Last week my 11-year-old
daughter saw it,

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.410
and she goes dad, why do
you have this sex book.

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:32.700
And I grabbed it back and said,
well that's for the course.

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:34.910
I'm teaching.

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:37.040
And I thought I'd
gotten away with it,

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:38.930
and everything was fine.

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:42.150
And then later that day she
texted all of our friends

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:44.330
about the new news
that what do you know,

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:48.960
her dad teaches sex ed at MIT.

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:53.950
Anyway this study concludes
that on average men

00:04:53.950 --> 00:05:00.430
have 74% more opposite-gender
partners than women.

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:01.925
There's one other
central claims.

00:05:10.389 --> 00:05:11.305
And this is in the US.

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:43.350
OK now, when you think about it
that sounds maybe reasonable,

00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:45.390
might be OK.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:49.750
But not according to ABC News.

00:05:49.750 --> 00:05:54.315
They did a poll of 1,500
people in the country, in 2004,

00:05:54.315 --> 00:05:59.090
and concluded that the average
disparity is much greater.

00:05:59.090 --> 00:06:01.950
In particular, in
this study, they

00:06:01.950 --> 00:06:05.210
said that the average
man has 20 partners--

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:07.100
I'm assuming over
their lifetime--

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:10.050
and the average woman has six.

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:12.636
And this gives a disparity 233%.

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:30.630
So ABC News did a smaller
survey says that it's 233% here,

00:06:30.630 --> 00:06:33.540
much more than 74%.

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:36.800
Now ABC News claimed
this is one of the most

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:39.060
scientific studies ever done.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:42.430
And there was a 2.5%
margin of error.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:45.540
Now we'll actually talk about
what that means mathematically

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:47.570
later in the term when
we do probability, and do

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.512
study polling.

00:06:49.512 --> 00:06:50.970
Now of course I
should also mention

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:52.770
that ABC News is
the one that said

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:57.720
Al Gore won the presidential
election in 2000.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:01.930
Now the study is called
American Sex Survey,

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:04.740
a Peak Between the Sheets.

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:06.530
That doesn't sound
so scientific.

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:09.990
And it was on TV, on
Primetime Live in 2004.

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:12.300
The promo for this
is really good.

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:16.740
It says, a groundbreaking ABC
News Primetime Live survey

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:20.030
finds a range of eye popping
sexual activities, fantasies,

00:07:20.030 --> 00:07:22.460
and attitudes in this
country, confirming

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:25.700
some conventional wisdom,
exploding some myths,

00:07:25.700 --> 00:07:28.560
and venturing where few
scientific surveys have

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:29.972
gone before.

00:07:29.972 --> 00:07:31.680
By the end of today,
we're going to agree

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:34.390
with that last statement.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:39.250
OK now who do you think's right?

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:41.980
University of Chicago.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:45.010
Who votes for 74% as
being pretty close?

00:07:45.010 --> 00:07:47.190
A few of you.

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:48.890
I've already slammed these guys.

00:07:48.890 --> 00:07:51.830
Who votes for ABC News
as being more accurate?

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:54.980
Yeah, nobody.

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:58.210
Who votes for no way to tell?

00:07:58.210 --> 00:08:00.360
I got some votes
there, all right.

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:03.230
So how do you
tackle this problem?

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:06.414
In theory we could do
our own 6.042 survey.

00:08:06.414 --> 00:08:08.080
I don't know how much
we'd really learn,

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:10.430
and for sure I'd get fired.

00:08:10.430 --> 00:08:14.030
So I don't think we're
going to do that.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:16.310
But fortunately, this
is the kind of question

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:17.940
that could be
handled, and actually

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:21.430
answered, by graph theory,
even though it might

00:08:21.430 --> 00:08:23.680
be more interesting to
interview thousands of people,

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:25.640
and find out what's going on.

00:08:25.640 --> 00:08:28.760
That's not as efficient
as using graphs.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:33.070
So let me start by
defining what a graph is.

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:37.210
Informally graph is just
a bunch of dots and lines

00:08:37.210 --> 00:08:40.374
connecting the dots, it's
actually very simple.

00:08:40.374 --> 00:08:41.165
So here's to graph.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:49.460
These are the nodes,
and they're connected

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:51.215
with these lines, called edges.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:57.530
And often the nodes,
and sometimes the edges,

00:08:57.530 --> 00:08:58.770
are labeled.

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:10.323
For example, we might call this
x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, and x7.

00:09:10.323 --> 00:09:13.090
So that's an example of a graph.

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:14.940
Now this being a
math class, we got

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:17.747
to give a formal
definition of a graph.

00:09:17.747 --> 00:09:19.580
And we'll usually use
the formal definition.

00:09:23.910 --> 00:09:41.310
A graph G is a pair of
sets often called V and E.

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:45.850
Where V is a set of elements
called vertices or nodes.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.330
And it has to be non-empty
here in this class.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:08.820
And we'll go back and forth
between vertices and nodes.

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:13.270
Even the text we use both
words interchangeably.

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:26.590
And E is a set of
2-item subsets and V,

00:10:26.590 --> 00:10:27.950
and they're called edges.

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:37.060
So for example, over
here in this picture,

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:48.950
V is the set of nodes is x1, x2,
x3, up to x7, that's the nodes.

00:10:48.950 --> 00:10:54.430
And E, the set of
edges, is pairs,

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:58.700
unordered pairs of vertices.

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:04.615
So for example
x1, x2 is an edge.

00:11:04.615 --> 00:11:07.660
And it's the same
as the set x2, x1,

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:09.210
doesn't matter the order here.

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:11.680
Later in a week or so, we'll
talk about directed graphs

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:14.600
where the order matters.

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:21.750
x1, x3 is also an
edge here, and so one.

00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:25.231
Think we've got, let's
see, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6,

00:11:25.231 --> 00:11:27.570
7 edges in this graph.

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:31.250
And the last one
would be x5, x7.

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:41.190
Edges are also sometimes written
with this notation, x1 line x2,

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:42.877
is another notation.

00:11:42.877 --> 00:11:44.960
And then later when you
talk about directed edges,

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:49.710
we'll put a little arrowhead
on one end of this.

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:52.110
Now the definition of a graph
is really pretty simple.

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:55.290
Just think of it as dots
and lines, if you want.

00:11:55.290 --> 00:11:59.440
But there's often differences
in how people define graphs.

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:04.550
For example, in this class we
don't allow the empty graph,

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:06.742
i.e. the graph with no nodes.

00:12:06.742 --> 00:12:08.950
So we're going to insist
that every graph has to have

00:12:08.950 --> 00:12:10.270
at least one node in it.

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:11.770
And that's just to
make the theorems

00:12:11.770 --> 00:12:13.010
we're going prove be true.

00:12:13.010 --> 00:12:14.510
Otherwise there's
some theorems that

00:12:14.510 --> 00:12:16.880
are false for the special
case of the empty graph.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:19.270
But we don't require the
graph to have any edges.

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:23.330
In fact, it's possible you
have a graph with nodes,

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:23.945
but no edges.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:28.560
For example, this graph.

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:29.310
Three-node graph.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:42.730
So here G equals VE,
V equals x1, x2, x3.

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:44.210
And E is just the empty set.

00:12:48.110 --> 00:12:53.060
Now for a general graph,
when you do have edges,

00:12:53.060 --> 00:13:04.005
we say that two nodes,
call them xi and xj,

00:13:04.005 --> 00:13:13.120
are adjacent if they're
connected by an edge, namely

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:18.160
if xi xj is an edge.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:24.630
All right so for example,
x5 is adjacent to x7,

00:13:24.630 --> 00:13:29.040
but it's not adjacent to
x4, there's no edge there.

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:37.810
Closely related is the
definition of the incidence.

00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:48.410
An edge E, which
is xixj, is said

00:13:48.410 --> 00:13:55.560
to be incident to its
end points, xi and xj.

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:06.400
OK so, for example, if I
labeled that edge as E, E

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:11.435
is the edge x1, x2, and this
incident to x1, and incident

00:14:11.435 --> 00:14:11.935
x2.

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:20.600
Then we can talk about
the degree of a node.

00:14:23.410 --> 00:14:38.180
The number of edges
incident to a node

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:40.030
is called the
degree of the node.

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:57.520
So for example, what's the
degree of x5 over here?

00:14:57.520 --> 00:15:05.010
3, so in this case, the
degree of x5 equals 3.

00:15:05.010 --> 00:15:10.920
The degree of x7 is 1.

00:15:10.920 --> 00:15:14.190
These guys all have
degree 0, there's

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:17.980
no edges incident to them.

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:21.790
Now in this class, we're going
to look at only simple graphs,

00:15:21.790 --> 00:15:23.000
at lease for a while.

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:40.950
A graph is simple if it has
no loops, or multiple edges.

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:53.750
Now a loop is an edge that only
connects up one node, that's

00:15:53.750 --> 00:15:56.250
a loop and we don't allow it.

00:15:56.250 --> 00:16:00.070
A multiple edge is we've got two
edges that are really the same,

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:02.980
they connect the same endpoints.

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:04.040
Also called a multi-edge.

00:16:08.290 --> 00:16:10.620
And those we're not going
to have in simple graphs.

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:11.975
We don't allow this.

00:16:11.975 --> 00:16:15.200
We don't allow that.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.920
Any questions so far
about what a graph is?

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:26.390
So how are we going
to use a graph

00:16:26.390 --> 00:16:32.470
to model the problem of
opposite-gender partners?

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:34.890
That's the question we're after.

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:38.052
So any thoughts about what
the nodes of the graph

00:16:38.052 --> 00:16:39.010
