00:35:23.740 --> 00:35:26.380
This can now get C3.

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:29.990
So we can have our exam from
9:00 to 11:00, which is better.

00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:32.375
All right, can anybody
do it in two colors?

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:44.935
Can anybody offer a reason why
two colors may not be possible?

00:35:47.536 --> 00:35:48.035
Yeah?

00:35:48.035 --> 00:35:51.575
AUDIENCE: Because let's say you
could do it with two colors.

00:35:51.575 --> 00:35:52.200
PROFESSOR: Yep.

00:35:52.200 --> 00:35:58.170
AUDIENCE: 6041 and 6002
have to be different colors.

00:35:58.170 --> 00:35:59.830
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:35:59.830 --> 00:36:03.500
AUDIENCE: 6042 can't be
C1, and it can't be C2.

00:36:03.500 --> 00:36:05.300
PROFESSOR: Yeah, good.

00:36:05.300 --> 00:36:09.130
So you can't in two colors,
because these three guys

00:36:09.130 --> 00:36:10.670
would violate that.

00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:11.990
You've got a triangle here.

00:36:11.990 --> 00:36:15.550
Each one of these guys has to
be different than the other two.

00:36:15.550 --> 00:36:16.920
So two colors can't work.

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:19.740
You've got to have at
least three in this case.

00:36:19.740 --> 00:36:20.760
So three is optimal.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:24.000
We have just shown
for this graph,

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.836
the chromatic number is three.

00:36:26.836 --> 00:36:33.300
All right, now in general doing
what we just did is very hard.

00:36:33.300 --> 00:36:35.680
No one knows a fast
algorithm for determining

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:38.560
the chromatic number.

00:36:38.560 --> 00:36:40.370
In fact, it's a weird
kind of problem,

00:36:40.370 --> 00:36:44.239
because it's easy enough to
check that a coloring is OK.

00:36:44.239 --> 00:36:46.530
If somebody put a coloring
on the board, you can check,

00:36:46.530 --> 00:36:48.420
oh that works really simply.

00:36:48.420 --> 00:36:52.070
Just check every edge, and make
sure the colors are different.

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:54.590
But figuring it out,
as best we know,

00:36:54.590 --> 00:36:57.840
you've got to try an exponential
number of possibilities.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:00.962
So if I had 100 nodes
here, my running time

00:37:00.962 --> 00:37:02.920
of the algorithm to check
all the possibilities

00:37:02.920 --> 00:37:04.800
would be exponential
and a hundred.

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:05.300
Yeah?

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:08.772
AUDIENCE: Can that number
just like the highest

00:37:08.772 --> 00:37:11.750
degree of each node, or nodes.

00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:13.015
PROFESSOR: Uh no.

00:37:13.015 --> 00:37:15.770
But it's no worse than
something like that,

00:37:15.770 --> 00:37:17.130
as we'll see a few minutes.

00:37:17.130 --> 00:37:18.750
That's a great observation.

00:37:18.750 --> 00:37:21.210
And we're going to come back
to that in a few minutes.

00:37:21.210 --> 00:37:24.180
But it's not just that.

00:37:24.180 --> 00:37:30.140
OK now in fact even figuring
out for an arbitrary graph

00:37:30.140 --> 00:37:33.320
if three colors
can be done, called

00:37:33.320 --> 00:37:36.290
the three-coloring problem,
that's really hard.

00:37:36.290 --> 00:37:39.570
No one knows how to solve that
in less than exponential time.

00:37:39.570 --> 00:37:43.000
In fact, one of these
NP-complete problems

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:44.340
is what it's called.

00:37:44.340 --> 00:37:47.870
How many people here don't
know about NP-completeness?

00:37:47.870 --> 00:37:49.822
Is everybody-- all
right so all of you

00:37:49.822 --> 00:37:51.030
haven't seen NP-completeness.

00:37:51.030 --> 00:37:56.120
OK so there is a class of
thousands of problems--

00:37:56.120 --> 00:38:00.230
in fact there's books list these
1,000 problems-- that are all

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:03.000
NP-complete, somebody's proved
they belong in the class.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.440
And what that means is
that if somebody gave you

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.300
a solution, like
a coloring here,

00:38:09.300 --> 00:38:13.850
it's easy to check really
quickly if it's valid.

00:38:13.850 --> 00:38:16.040
But figuring it
out is really hard.

00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:17.790
And if you figured
out how to solve

00:38:17.790 --> 00:38:19.761
one of those
thousands of problems,

00:38:19.761 --> 00:38:22.260
like suddenly you figured out
how to tell if any graph could

00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:25.610
work with three colors, you
would solve automatically

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:28.429
all other thousands in the book.

00:38:28.429 --> 00:38:30.470
So it's this book of
problems you will constantly

00:38:30.470 --> 00:38:33.952
run into in your career
in computer science.

00:38:33.952 --> 00:38:35.410
And it's bad when
you run into one,

00:38:35.410 --> 00:38:38.200
because there's no good
algorithm to solve it known.

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:40.065
But if you just
solved one of them,

00:38:40.065 --> 00:38:43.620
the other thousands would
suddenly be solvable quickly.

00:38:43.620 --> 00:38:46.540
Even better, you win a
million dollar prize.

00:38:46.540 --> 00:38:48.000
One of these
Millennium Prizes we

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.860
talked about the first lecture.

00:38:50.860 --> 00:38:53.880
Even if you show you can't
find a fast algorithm for one

00:38:53.880 --> 00:38:57.000
of them, that means that known
of them have fast algorithms,

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.397
and you also get
a million dollars.

00:38:59.397 --> 00:39:01.980
So this is the central problem
in computer science, and theory

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:04.410
computing, is whether
or not you could solve

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:07.060
these NP-complete problems.

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:09.770
Now actually lots of
people have claim to do it.

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:12.300
And in fact, there was a
lot of buzz in the community

00:39:12.300 --> 00:39:15.110
about a month ago when
actually a reputable researcher

00:39:15.110 --> 00:39:17.370
at HP Labs said he'd done it.

00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:21.630
He proved that you can't
solve NP-complete problems.

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:24.100
And he got people going for
probably at least a week,

00:39:24.100 --> 00:39:26.420
until they discovered
a fatal flaw.

00:39:26.420 --> 00:39:29.550
And the proof was
actually bogus.

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:31.770
So no one still knows
if you can solve

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:34.770
these NP-complete
problems quickly.

00:39:34.770 --> 00:39:38.620
Now the problem is, in practice,
you run into these things

00:39:38.620 --> 00:39:40.430
all the time, like
MIT really does

00:39:40.430 --> 00:39:42.430
have to schedule the exams.

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:43.680
So you've got to do something.

00:39:43.680 --> 00:39:46.690
You can't just go say, hey
it's NP-complete, so no exams

00:39:46.690 --> 00:39:48.870
this year, or whatever.

00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:52.970
That's not going to fly,
so you got to do something.

00:39:52.970 --> 00:39:55.320
So now this is a
problem-- many of you

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:58.510
when you go into careers, you're
going to be faced with this.

00:39:58.510 --> 00:40:00.250
You got to do something.

00:40:00.250 --> 00:40:06.010
Any thoughts about an algorithm
for coloring graphs that might

00:40:06.010 --> 00:40:07.880
use a small number of colors?

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:10.335
It doesn't have to
always work, or you're

00:40:10.335 --> 00:40:11.960
going to win a lot
of money if it does.

00:40:11.960 --> 00:40:14.300
But a simple
algorithm, you can't

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:16.590
take either the 100 steps.

00:40:16.590 --> 00:40:19.690
You got to be linear,
probably, or quadratic time.

00:40:19.690 --> 00:40:22.800
That could get you a
small number of colors.

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:25.860
Any thoughts about
what you'd do?

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:26.360
Yeah?

00:40:26.360 --> 00:40:28.770
AUDIENCE: The number
of degrees and nodes?

00:40:28.770 --> 00:40:30.590
PROFESSOR: The
number-- what about it?

00:40:30.590 --> 00:40:33.220
AUDIENCE: The highest
degree and that node,

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:34.799
the 6042 is [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:34.799 --> 00:40:35.465
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:40:35.465 --> 00:40:38.700
AUDIENCE: So you could use that.

00:40:38.700 --> 00:40:40.210
PROFESSOR: Good, all right.

00:40:40.210 --> 00:40:42.200
So what do I do with
that-- so I found

00:40:42.200 --> 00:40:45.130
a node with a high
degree, there's

00:40:45.130 --> 00:40:47.030
three of them have
degree three here.

00:40:47.030 --> 00:40:48.806
What do I do with them?

00:40:48.806 --> 00:40:52.324
AUDIENCE: Pick a
different color to.

00:40:52.324 --> 00:40:53.740
PROFESSOR: Pick a
different color,

00:40:53.740 --> 00:40:55.890
that means I've colored
some of the others.

00:40:55.890 --> 00:40:59.040
If I pick a different
color, do I start with them,

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:03.030
or do I finish with
a high degree nodes?

00:41:03.030 --> 00:41:05.807
Because you've got to
assign the colors to them.

00:41:05.807 --> 00:41:07.890
And high degree is important
to be thinking about.

00:41:07.890 --> 00:41:10.431
We're going to prove a theorem
in just a minute about related

00:41:10.431 --> 00:41:11.730
to degree and coloring.

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:14.800
AUDIENCE: Start with them.

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:17.310
PROFESSOR: Start with
them, and do what with it?

00:41:17.310 --> 00:41:18.498
Color?

00:41:18.498 --> 00:41:22.890
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and then assign
the ones that aren't connected

00:41:22.890 --> 00:41:26.310
[INAUDIBLE] to the same slots.

00:41:26.310 --> 00:41:29.250
PROFESSOR: OK, so I could--
here's a degree of theory

00:41:29.250 --> 00:41:32.630
now I can start with
color one for that.

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:34.190
And then what do I do next?

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:38.372
I pick-- its neighbors have to
get different colors, I guess.

00:41:38.372 --> 00:41:39.830
You'd start coloring
the neighbors.

00:41:39.830 --> 00:41:42.305
AUDIENCE: My first
instinct would be

00:41:42.305 --> 00:41:44.780
to color all the [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:48.250 --> 00:41:49.530
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:41:49.530 --> 00:41:51.320
And what color
would use for them?

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:52.702
AUDIENCE: Different ones.

00:41:52.702 --> 00:41:54.660
PROFESSOR: Different ones
if they're connected,

00:41:54.660 --> 00:41:57.790
or if they're not connected
you'd still use different ones?

00:41:57.790 --> 00:42:00.670
AUDIENCE: Only if
they're connected.

00:42:00.670 --> 00:42:02.940
PROFESSOR: Only they're
connected use different ones.

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:06.901
And so if they're not connected,
you'd use the same colors?

00:42:06.901 --> 00:42:07.401
Yeah?

00:42:10.190 --> 00:42:14.620
You're going close, and it
actually works pretty well.

00:42:14.620 --> 00:42:17.910
The underlying principle you're
sort of thinking about here

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:21.160
is you've got some notion
of the order in which you're

00:42:21.160 --> 00:42:22.985
going to process your graph.

00:42:22.985 --> 00:42:25.110
And you're going to start
with a high degree nodes,

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:26.530
in your case.

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:28.200
And as you go
along, you're going

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:30.950
to start coloring the nodes.

00:42:30.950 --> 00:42:33.990
And you're going to make
sure you color them legally.

00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:37.920
And it sounds like you're going
to color them with a low color

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:39.270
as you go along.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:44.860
And that is probably the most
basic graph coloring approach.

00:42:44.860 --> 00:42:48.560
And almost you could almost
say is a generic approach.

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:52.091
So let's define that, and then
see prove some facts about it.

00:42:56.710 --> 00:42:58.860
Most of the graph coloring
algorithms in practice

00:42:58.860 --> 00:43:01.070
are based on this approach.

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:05.320
And we're going to call it the
basic graph coloring algorithm.

00:43:14.240 --> 00:43:20.840
And for our graph G, with
vertices V, and edges E.

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:31.080
So the first step is going to be
to order the nodes from 1 to n.

00:43:34.110 --> 00:43:35.850
Now in your case,
you were suggesting

00:43:35.850 --> 00:43:39.700
an ordering where I have
the high degree nodes first.

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:41.217
All right.

00:43:41.217 --> 00:43:43.050
But for now we're not
going to specify that.

00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:47.290
We're going to make it
any ordering you want.

00:43:47.290 --> 00:43:50.080
And then we're going to
have a notion of an order

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:51.490
on the colors, as well.

00:43:57.815 --> 00:43:59.190
And I don't know
how many colors,

00:43:59.190 --> 00:44:02.480
but they're going to be
numbered 1, 2, and so forth.

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:08.773
And then we're going to process
the nodes one at a time,

00:44:08.773 --> 00:44:13.860
to N. We color the
nodes, what is step I,

00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:18.430
we color the Ith node V sub i
with the lowest legal color.

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:28.490
And by the legal I mean you
don't color at the same node

00:44:28.490 --> 00:44:31.640
as another node that's already
been colored the same that it's

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:32.602
adjacent to.

00:44:40.790 --> 00:44:43.290
All right so let's try this.

00:44:43.290 --> 00:44:47.480
In fact, this is sort of the
algorithm I used initially

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:50.700
to color exam graph over there.

00:44:54.508 --> 00:44:58.230
All right, so
let's look at that.

00:44:58.230 --> 00:45:04.310
So let's say we-- let me
erase the colors here, and put

00:45:04.310 --> 00:45:05.465
an ordering on the nodes.

00:45:08.100 --> 00:45:12.230
So let's say I ordered
them with 6034 first,

00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:15.060
so this would be V1.

00:45:15.060 --> 00:45:18.390
Then 6041 is V2.

00:45:18.390 --> 00:45:23.380
Then V3, V4, V5.

00:45:26.290 --> 00:45:30.552
If that's my ordering, what
color would I assign to 6034?

00:45:30.552 --> 00:45:31.730
AUDIENCE: One.

00:45:31.730 --> 00:45:35.140
PROFESSOR: One, C1, I'd
color it first to get C1.

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:38.860
What color does 6041 get?

00:45:38.860 --> 00:45:41.420
C1, as well, it's the
lowest possible color

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:47.110
that's legal, and is not hooked
to this guy, so C1 is legal.

00:45:47.110 --> 00:45:49.810
What color do I give here?

00:45:49.810 --> 00:45:52.480
C2.

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:59.170
Then I color this one next
C-- can't do C2, can't do C1,

00:45:59.170 --> 00:46:01.460
so I pick C3.

00:46:01.460 --> 00:46:03.500
And then I get to
6042 last, and I

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:07.220
can't do one, two, or
three, so I do four.

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:09.150
All right so algorithm,
with that ordering,

00:46:09.150 --> 00:46:10.860
gave four colors.

00:46:10.860 --> 00:46:14.970
However we know there's a way
to do a different ordering that

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:19.220
gives us three colors.

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:20.840
In particular,
let's see if we do

00:46:20.840 --> 00:46:23.150
this what happens if we
use this other ordering.

00:46:23.150 --> 00:46:26.050
Let me erase these.

00:46:26.050 --> 00:46:33.960
Say that's V1, V2, V3, V4, V5.

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:40.140
Now I get C1, this
will be C2, C1.

00:46:43.920 --> 00:46:45.670
What's this one get?

00:46:45.670 --> 00:46:46.320
C2.

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:49.350
Ah, much better.

00:46:49.350 --> 00:46:50.800
C3.

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:54.880
So different orderings result
in different numbers of colors

00:46:54.880 --> 00:46:56.380
here.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:47:00.850
So the whole art now becomes
finding a clever ordering.

00:47:00.850 --> 00:47:03.210
And so many people have
already had good ideas,

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:05.850
pick the largest
degree nodes first.

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:11.740
And in fact, if you simulate
the algorithm on lots of graphs,

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:16.140
you do better on average when
you color the larger degree

00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:17.820
nodes first.

00:47:17.820 --> 00:47:20.850
And then if you start to
use more exotic orderings,

00:47:20.850 --> 00:47:22.762
you can do even better.

00:47:22.762 --> 00:47:24.720
If you take a lot of
graphs that are out there,

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:26.719
and run your algorithm,
and see how well you do,

00:47:26.719 --> 00:47:29.540
you do better with more
sophisticated orderings.

00:47:29.540 --> 00:47:34.550
In fact, this was my
senior thesis back

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:36.290
when I was
undergraduate student.

00:47:36.290 --> 00:47:39.650
I was trying to figure out
better and better orderings

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:41.690
that worked for graphs.

00:47:41.690 --> 00:47:44.820
And at the time it caused
a bit of a problem.

00:47:44.820 --> 00:47:47.470
I was a undergraduate
at Princeton.

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:49.120
And Princeton, to
this day I think,

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:52.090
still has exams after the
holidays, the Christmas

00:47:52.090 --> 00:47:54.010
holidays, New Year's holidays.

00:47:54.010 --> 00:47:57.810
And the students wanted to have
the exams before Christmas,

00:47:57.810 --> 00:47:59.770
because they hated going
home for the holiday,

00:47:59.770 --> 00:48:01.790
and then you've got to
worry about your exams

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:03.270
when you come back.

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:06.050
And the faculty said
no, there's no way

00:48:06.050 --> 00:48:09.570
to get them all compressed
into a small number of days.

00:48:09.570 --> 00:48:12.010
Now I wasn't aware of
all that of the time.

00:48:12.010 --> 00:48:14.255
But my thesis was go
figure out good ordering.

00:48:14.255 --> 00:48:15.880
So I tried lots of
different orderings.

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:17.850
And I tried the
largest degree first,

00:48:17.850 --> 00:48:21.730
and recursive versions of that
actually worked very well.

00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:25.620
And then tried it on the
Princeton exam graph.

00:48:25.620 --> 00:48:28.310
And lo and behold, you could
actually squish it down,

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:30.200
so you could give all
the exams, I think was,

00:48:30.200 --> 00:48:33.960
4 and 1/2 days, plenty of time
to give them before Christmas.

00:48:33.960 --> 00:48:36.330
Which caused a fair of
scandal at the time,

00:48:36.330 --> 00:48:38.670
because then the faculty
had to come clean

00:48:38.670 --> 00:48:40.730
that they just didn't
want to bother having

00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:44.180
the exams before Christmas.

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:46.770
Now this algorithm is
an example of what's

00:48:46.770 --> 00:48:48.780
known as a greedy algorithm.

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:52.930
Now in a greedy algorithm
it's always simple.

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:55.360
You just go one
step after the next,

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:57.760
taking the best you
can do at each stop.

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:00.670
You never go back and try
to make things better.

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:03.950
You never do hill climbing, if
you're familiar with that term.

00:49:03.950 --> 00:49:07.010
You just always keep it simple,
one thing after the next,

00:49:07.010 --> 00:49:08.830
very fast.

00:49:08.830 --> 00:49:10.770
Sometimes it works
great in practice.

00:49:10.770 --> 00:49:12.570
Sometimes it doesn't.

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:16.860
But it's always where you start,
some simple approach like this.

00:49:16.860 --> 00:49:20.770
Now this algorithm
actually, even

00:49:20.770 --> 00:49:22.850
if you don't try to
monkey with the ordering,

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:25.140
even for a worst case
ordering of the nodes,

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:28.930
that actually does pretty
good for a lot of graphs.

00:49:28.930 --> 00:49:30.730
And in fact, it
does really well--

00:49:30.730 --> 00:49:33.040
as somebody already
asked about--

00:49:33.040 --> 00:49:35.510
if all the nodes
have low degree.

00:49:35.510 --> 00:49:37.060
So let's state
that as a theorem.

00:49:37.060 --> 00:49:38.518
And then we're
going to prove that.

00:49:44.329 --> 00:49:54.330
So if every node in a graph
G has degree, at most,

00:49:54.330 --> 00:49:58.550
d-- so that's the biggest
degree in the graph, D-- then

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:16.480
this basic algorithm uses, at
most, d plus 1 colors for G.

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:19.920
No matter what the
ordering is, you'll

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:23.490
never do worse than
d plus 1 colors.

00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:28.840
So what's the value of d for
our exam graph over here?

00:50:28.840 --> 00:50:30.180
d is 3.

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:33.240
Every node has degree,
at most, three.

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:37.120
And so it says, that no matter
what ordering you picked here,

00:50:37.120 --> 00:50:39.350
you'd get at most four colors.

00:50:39.350 --> 00:50:40.350
Now you might do better.

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:42.620
In fact, we found an
ordering that got three.

00:50:42.620 --> 00:50:45.940
So it's possible to do better.

00:50:45.940 --> 00:50:49.040
So let's prove this fact
because this makes a difference.

00:50:49.040 --> 00:50:53.260
Say you have a graph
with hundreds of nodes.

00:50:53.260 --> 00:50:55.716
But every node has
degree, at most, three.

00:50:55.716 --> 00:50:58.560
Well that says you only
need four colors even,

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:01.840
if the graph has 1,000 nodes,
and that's very useful.

00:51:01.840 --> 00:51:04.580
So in that kind of
situation it does very well.

00:51:04.580 --> 00:51:05.525
So let's prove that.

00:51:09.570 --> 00:51:12.733
Any ideas as to what proof
technique we're going to use?

00:51:12.733 --> 00:51:14.705
AUDIENCE: Invariant.

00:51:14.705 --> 00:51:17.120
PROFESSOR: Invariant, close.

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:19.560
Not quite an
invariant, but close.

00:51:19.560 --> 00:51:22.450
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:22.450 --> 00:51:23.404
PROFESSOR: What?

00:51:23.404 --> 00:51:24.820
AUDIENCE: Well
ordering principle.

00:51:24.820 --> 00:51:26.420
PROFESSOR: You know well
ordering principle, yeah,

00:51:26.420 --> 00:51:28.503
we're going to use the
equivalent version of that.

00:51:28.503 --> 00:51:31.024
We're going to use induction.

00:51:31.024 --> 00:51:33.190
If you like well-- it's
equivalent to well ordering.

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:35.314
If you like well ordering
you could do it that way.

00:51:35.314 --> 00:51:38.400
I think it's easier
using induction here.

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:39.765
So the proof is by induction.

00:51:45.110 --> 00:51:46.720
All right so the
first thing we need

00:51:46.720 --> 00:51:47.845
is an induction hypothesis.

00:51:50.950 --> 00:51:54.450
Any thoughts about what the
induction hypothesis should be?

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:55.202
Yeah?

00:51:55.202 --> 00:52:01.270
AUDIENCE: If you have a
graph with n nodes then

00:52:01.270 --> 00:52:06.150
where the degree of any nodes
is less than [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:06.150 --> 00:52:08.090
then you can do it.

00:52:08.090 --> 00:52:09.090
PROFESSOR: That's great.

00:52:09.090 --> 00:52:12.030
You're going to do really
well on the midterm,

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:14.450
because you put an
n into this thing,

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:16.570
but there's not an
n here to start.

00:52:16.570 --> 00:52:18.320
What are most
people going to do--

00:52:18.320 --> 00:52:20.210
we used to ask this actually.

00:52:20.210 --> 00:52:22.830
We asked this once on
a test many years ago,

00:52:22.830 --> 00:52:25.820
and it was an utter disaster,
because did everybody do?

00:52:25.820 --> 00:52:28.832
May be one student, or
two, put an n into there.

00:52:28.832 --> 00:52:31.290
But what's the naturally thing
to do to induct on here when

00:52:31.290 --> 00:52:34.560
you look at this statement?

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:37.760
You're going to induct on d,
because the first thing you do

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:39.680
is you make this be your
induction hypothesis.

00:52:39.680 --> 00:52:41.950
There's only one thing
to use, so you're

00:52:41.950 --> 00:52:44.910
going to have your
predicate be p of d,

00:52:44.910 --> 00:52:47.014
and it's going to be that.

00:52:47.014 --> 00:52:49.680
Now It didn't occur to us that's
what everybody was going to do,

00:52:49.680 --> 00:52:50.560
but it should have.

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:53.220
They all did that and
it was a disaster.

00:52:53.220 --> 00:52:56.010
Because if you do
this, well you've

00:52:56.010 --> 00:53:00.280
got to take a graph with
maximum degree d, or d plus 1

00:53:00.280 --> 00:53:03.200
in the inductive step,
pull out all the nodes

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:07.021
with degree d plus 1 to get
a graph with now degree d.

00:53:07.021 --> 00:53:07.770
And that's a mess.

00:53:07.770 --> 00:53:10.410
You just pulled out a lot
of nodes, potentially.

00:53:10.410 --> 00:53:14.650
Color that in d plus 1 colors,
now put all that junk back in.

00:53:14.650 --> 00:53:17.180
And say only used
one more color.

00:53:17.180 --> 00:53:18.520
Nightmare.

00:53:18.520 --> 00:53:21.300
And these were MIT
students under pressure.

00:53:21.300 --> 00:53:23.330
It was a nightmare.

00:53:23.330 --> 00:53:24.410
So that does not work.

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:27.410
And in fact, we will ask
an induction question

00:53:27.410 --> 00:53:29.960
on graphs on every test
you take in this course.

00:53:29.960 --> 00:53:31.190
It will happen.

00:53:31.190 --> 00:53:34.850
And so usually,
with induction, you

00:53:34.850 --> 00:53:36.580
take this as your
induction hypothesis.

00:53:36.580 --> 00:53:38.650
With graphs, you
have to be careful.

00:53:38.650 --> 00:53:41.830
And worst part about
this is we tell people

00:53:41.830 --> 00:53:45.950
when this doesn't work, use a
stronger induction hypothesis.

00:53:45.950 --> 00:53:48.280
So students tried
to make a stronger,

00:53:48.280 --> 00:53:51.900
but they're still stuck on d,
and it was still a disaster.

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:53.930
With graphs, you do
something different.

00:53:53.930 --> 00:53:56.240
And the first thing you
do with a graph, usually,

00:53:56.240 --> 00:53:58.385
is put n in here.

00:53:58.385 --> 00:54:00.510
And if it doesn't work with
n, the number of nodes,

00:54:00.510 --> 00:54:03.410
you put in e the
number of edges.

00:54:03.410 --> 00:54:05.120
And induct on that.

00:54:05.120 --> 00:54:08.460
And so what you said is
exactly the right thing to do.

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:11.270
Don't do this, or least don't
spend too much time on it.

00:54:11.270 --> 00:54:13.360
Pretty quickly try this.

00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:17.970
If every end node graph--
if every node in an n

00:54:17.970 --> 00:54:23.840
node graph G has
degree at most degree,

00:54:23.840 --> 00:54:27.070
then the basic algorithm uses
at most d, plus one colors.

00:54:27.070 --> 00:54:30.350
And now you induct on n.

00:54:30.350 --> 00:54:33.100
And almost always on graphs,
that's the first thing to try.

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:37.270
Even if it's not in
your theorem statement.

00:54:37.270 --> 00:54:39.900
Any questions about that?

00:54:46.940 --> 00:54:49.570
Well let's start
with this, and see

00:54:49.570 --> 00:54:51.256
if we can make this one work.

00:55:02.230 --> 00:55:04.140
So what's the next
step in our proof?

00:55:04.140 --> 00:55:06.560
What do we got to do?

00:55:06.560 --> 00:55:07.380
Base case.

00:55:11.890 --> 00:55:14.750
And the base case will
be, not n equals 0,

00:55:14.750 --> 00:55:19.300
because we can't have a zero
node graph, but n equals 1.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:22.940
And how many edges do we have?

00:55:22.940 --> 00:55:23.440
Zero.

00:55:23.440 --> 00:55:25.190
If there's one node,
we don't allow loops,

00:55:25.190 --> 00:55:33.140
so it's zero edges, which means
that the degree of our graph

00:55:33.140 --> 00:55:36.380
has to be zero.

00:55:36.380 --> 00:55:37.780
There's no edges.

00:55:37.780 --> 00:55:39.900
And of course there's
only one node,

00:55:39.900 --> 00:55:44.140
so one color is going
to work, and that

00:55:44.140 --> 00:55:46.340
happens to equal d plus 1.

00:55:49.460 --> 00:55:52.110
All right, so the
base case is true.

00:55:52.110 --> 00:55:55.110
For one node graphs,
you can always

00:55:55.110 --> 00:55:59.010
use d plus 1 colors,
where d is the max degree.

00:55:59.010 --> 00:56:01.210
All right, next we have
the inductive step.

00:56:05.500 --> 00:56:14.425
So here we assume P n is
true for the induction.

00:56:20.330 --> 00:56:23.130
And now we look at an
n plus 1 node graph

00:56:23.130 --> 00:56:26.620
to show P n plus 1 is true.

00:56:26.620 --> 00:56:35.240
So we let G be any
N plus 1 node graph.

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:39.152
We got to show you can
color it in d plus 1 colors.

00:56:41.810 --> 00:56:48.790
And let's let d be the
max degree, the largest

00:56:48.790 --> 00:56:56.020
degree in G.

00:56:56.020 --> 00:57:01.180
We've got to show we can
color it in d plus 1 colors.

00:57:01.180 --> 00:57:03.120
Well the basic
algorithm, let's say.

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.680
First thing we do is
we order the nodes

00:57:05.680 --> 00:57:06.954
in an arbitrary order.

00:57:10.363 --> 00:57:13.700
And we're going to show
whatever order you pick is OK.

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:28.185
All right so what are the nodes?

00:57:38.740 --> 00:57:41.200
Anyway at all.

00:57:41.200 --> 00:57:45.690
Now how am I going to use
the induction hypothesis?

00:57:45.690 --> 00:57:49.900
I know, I can assume,
the for any N node graph

00:57:49.900 --> 00:57:54.550
I can color it in the
max degree plus 1 colors.

00:57:54.550 --> 00:57:56.940
How am I going to use that
to help me color G here,

00:57:56.940 --> 00:57:58.260
the n plus 1 node graph?

00:57:58.260 --> 00:58:00.690
Any thoughts?

00:58:00.690 --> 00:58:01.190
Yeah?

00:58:01.190 --> 00:58:03.860
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:06.920
PROFESSOR: Yeah, let's
create an n node graph

00:58:06.920 --> 00:58:09.410
by looking at these
nodes, and taking

00:58:09.410 --> 00:58:12.310
this one out of the time being.

00:58:12.310 --> 00:58:15.910
Remove the last V n plus
1 node in the order.

00:58:15.910 --> 00:58:19.400
That leaves an n node graph.

00:58:19.400 --> 00:58:22.310
So let's write that down.

00:58:22.310 --> 00:58:33.120
We remove the n plus 1 from G.
And that creates a new graph,

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:38.530
call it G prime with vertices,
V prime and edges, E prime.

00:58:38.530 --> 00:58:40.925
So we create a new graph
by removing that node.

00:58:43.640 --> 00:58:46.240
And we remove all the
edges tied to that node.

00:58:46.240 --> 00:58:50.360
So for example over
here, the last node

00:58:50.360 --> 00:58:56.150
was 6042, so we take out
6042, and all these edges.

00:58:56.150 --> 00:58:59.116
And this is a graph
that we're left with.

00:59:02.370 --> 00:59:06.190
That graph has n nodes.

00:59:06.190 --> 00:59:08.637
What's the maximum
degree in G prime?

00:59:11.910 --> 00:59:18.054
When I pull out a node, can
the degree of any node go up?

00:59:18.054 --> 00:59:21.320
No, I'm just taking stuff out.

00:59:21.320 --> 00:59:27.930
So I know that G prime has
maximum degree, at most, d.

00:59:27.930 --> 00:59:30.370
The degree didn't
go up of any node.

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:38.430
Might have gone down,
but it didn't go up.

00:59:38.430 --> 00:59:44.045
So G prime has max degree, at
most, d, and it has n nodes.

00:59:47.440 --> 00:59:50.440
So we can use the
induction hypothesis P n.

00:59:53.360 --> 01:00:01.320
It says that the basic
algorithm uses d plus 1,

01:00:01.320 --> 01:00:09.758
at most, d plus 1 colors
for nodes V1 to V n.

01:00:13.104 --> 01:00:14.260
Any questions about that?

01:00:17.140 --> 01:00:22.140
So if this were the n plus first
node, last node in the ordering

01:00:22.140 --> 01:00:24.090
take it out.

01:00:24.090 --> 01:00:26.490
The basic algorithm now,
take the same order here,

01:00:26.490 --> 01:00:33.850
V1, V2, V3, V4, basic, we'll
color that in d plus 1 colors.

01:00:33.850 --> 01:00:36.950
And all I have left is
to give this guy color,

01:00:36.950 --> 01:00:41.360
and I'll have color G. Question?

01:00:41.360 --> 01:00:43.640
No.

01:00:43.640 --> 01:00:45.600
All right.

01:00:45.600 --> 01:00:48.820
So by induction I've colored
these guys, V1 to V2,

01:00:48.820 --> 01:00:51.760
and d plus 1 colors, all
that I have left to do

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:56.000
is color V n plus 1.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:59.585
And hopefully we're not
going to use color d plus 2,

01:00:59.585 --> 01:01:02.450
because then we sort
of-- it wouldn't work.

01:01:02.450 --> 01:01:04.953
We got to use one of
the first d plus 1.

01:01:12.330 --> 01:01:14.370
All right, so let's
look at V n plus 1.

01:01:17.110 --> 01:01:25.780
And let's call its
neighbors in G, U1, U2, Ud.

01:01:25.780 --> 01:01:31.630
It has, at most d neighbors,
because every node in G has,

01:01:31.630 --> 01:01:34.320
at most, degree d.

01:01:34.320 --> 01:01:35.980
A neighbor's a node
you're adjacent to.

01:01:38.840 --> 01:01:45.950
All right so, V n plus 1 has at
most d neighbors, is adjacent

01:01:45.950 --> 01:01:48.061
to, at most, d other nodes.

01:01:51.220 --> 01:01:54.470
Now what does that
mean about the color I

01:01:54.470 --> 01:01:56.990
can use on V n plus 1?

01:01:59.540 --> 01:02:04.605
What do I know about what
color I can use for that?

01:02:04.605 --> 01:02:05.105
Yeah?

01:02:05.105 --> 01:02:10.070
AUDIENCE: It can't be any of
the colors of U1, U2, and so on.

01:02:10.070 --> 01:02:12.850
PROFESSOR: It can't be any
one of these colors that

01:02:12.850 --> 01:02:14.860
were assigned here.

01:02:14.860 --> 01:02:16.110
That's true.

01:02:16.110 --> 01:02:19.440
So how many colors
got ruled out?

01:02:19.440 --> 01:02:23.300
At most d, and how
many am I working with?

01:02:23.300 --> 01:02:25.560
d Plus 1.

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:29.580
So I got one left
that I can use safely.

01:02:29.580 --> 01:02:30.920
OK.

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:35.660
So this means there
exists at least one color

01:02:35.660 --> 01:02:37.890
in my set of d plus 1 colors.

01:02:42.560 --> 01:02:47.575
It's not used by any neighbor.

01:02:53.660 --> 01:02:56.390
And we're going to give
V n plus 1 that color.

01:03:07.150 --> 01:03:07.650
All right.

01:03:07.650 --> 01:03:12.350
So now I've colored every node
in G, the n plus 1 node graph,

01:03:12.350 --> 01:03:15.315
safely using a total
of d plus 1 colors.

01:03:18.692 --> 01:03:25.050
So that means the
basic algorithm uses,

01:03:25.050 --> 01:03:33.340
at most, d plus 1 colors,
on G. That means P n plus 1

01:03:33.340 --> 01:03:37.815
is true-- whoops-- and
the induction is complete.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:44.853
Any questions?

01:03:44.853 --> 01:03:45.353
Yeah.

01:03:45.353 --> 01:03:49.281
AUDIENCE: Could you also
start from the other way,

01:03:49.281 --> 01:03:55.664
and start 1, go to 2 nodes,
3 nodes at each step keeping

01:03:55.664 --> 01:03:59.101
all nodes at all other nodes.

01:03:59.101 --> 01:04:02.080
[INAUDIBLE]

01:04:02.080 --> 01:04:05.308
PROFESSOR: What do you mean by
keeping all nodes connected?

01:04:05.308 --> 01:04:16.264
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] each
node has an edge connecting

01:04:16.264 --> 01:04:17.804
to each other one.

01:04:17.804 --> 01:04:19.720
PROFESSOR: OK so, then
I get a specific graph.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:24.240
I start with this, I add a
node and make it adjacent.

01:04:24.240 --> 01:04:25.680
I add a node and
make it adjacent.

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:26.554
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:04:32.410 --> 01:04:33.904
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:04:33.904 --> 01:04:36.620
So you've constructed
a particular graph.

01:04:36.620 --> 01:04:40.260
This is actually called, for
the n nodes, it's called Kn,

01:04:40.260 --> 01:04:45.010
is the n node complete
graph, also called a clique,

01:04:45.010 --> 01:04:49.100
like a clique of friends, where
everybody likes everybody,

01:04:49.100 --> 01:04:52.350
in a clique.

01:04:52.350 --> 01:04:55.660
And in fact for n here,
for those n nodes,

01:04:55.660 --> 01:04:58.940
what's the max degree?

01:04:58.940 --> 01:05:01.440
Max degree is n minus 1.

01:05:01.440 --> 01:05:03.420
What's the chromatic
number of this graph?

01:05:05.986 --> 01:05:07.485
What's the minimum
number of colors?

01:05:07.485 --> 01:05:09.156
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:05:09.156 --> 01:05:11.030
PROFESSOR: And they all
have to be different,

01:05:11.030 --> 01:05:12.890
which is d plus 1.

01:05:12.890 --> 01:05:16.420
So you have built
a special graph

01:05:16.420 --> 01:05:19.560
for which the optimum of
number colors is d plus 1.

01:05:19.560 --> 01:05:23.630
But that is not a proof that
this is true for all graphs.

01:05:23.630 --> 01:05:26.384
Because you've looked at
a particular graph here.

01:05:26.384 --> 01:05:27.259
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:30.222 --> 01:05:31.180
PROFESSOR: What's that?

01:05:31.180 --> 01:05:34.760
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] It means
that you can still use your

01:05:34.760 --> 01:05:36.138
less than or equal to sign.

01:05:36.138 --> 01:05:38.490
PROFESSOR: I see,
so you'd add a node,

01:05:38.490 --> 01:05:41.182
and it's only connected
to a few of them.

01:05:41.182 --> 01:05:43.015
AUDIENCE: No, it's
connected to all of them,

01:05:43.015 --> 01:05:45.930
but it still implies
that you need less than

01:05:45.930 --> 01:05:47.050
or equal to the colors.

01:05:47.050 --> 01:05:49.083
It turns out it
happens to be equal to.

01:05:49.083 --> 01:05:50.832
PROFESSOR: Yes, in
this case that's right.

01:05:50.832 --> 01:05:52.510
So you've made an
argument for this case

01:05:52.510 --> 01:05:54.060
where it actually
is equal, but that

01:05:54.060 --> 01:05:55.200
only worked for this graph.

01:05:55.200 --> 01:05:59.310
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
worse case.

01:05:59.310 --> 01:06:02.666
PROFESSOR: It is the worst
case, so it meets the bound.

01:06:02.666 --> 01:06:04.290
It shows you cannot
improve this bound.

01:06:04.290 --> 01:06:06.052
