The most famous example
of graph coloring

01:20:17.720 --> 01:20:21.670
is the map coloring problem,
with the four coloring theorem.

01:20:21.670 --> 01:20:25.800
And so here, every
country is a node.

01:20:25.800 --> 01:20:27.727
Adjacent countries have
an edge between them,

01:20:27.727 --> 01:20:29.810
because you don't want to
color adjacent countries

01:20:29.810 --> 01:20:31.480
the same color,
or you can't tell

01:20:31.480 --> 01:20:34.730
they're different countries.

01:20:34.730 --> 01:20:36.990
Now the last example
we can talk about

01:20:36.990 --> 01:20:40.000
is an important problem
in communication theory,

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:43.630
communication networks, where
again coloring comes up.

01:20:43.630 --> 01:20:48.100
Now here you need to assign
frequencies to radio stations,

01:20:48.100 --> 01:20:49.035
or the cell towers.

01:20:49.035 --> 01:20:54.510
It comes up in mobile networks,
or just in with radio stations.

01:20:54.510 --> 01:20:59.370
And if two towers have
an overlapping area,

01:20:59.370 --> 01:21:01.290
they can't be given
the same frequency,

01:21:01.290 --> 01:21:05.540
so you get collisions
between the towers.

01:21:05.540 --> 01:21:07.110
And frequencies
are very expensive.

01:21:07.110 --> 01:21:08.901
Companies pay the
government a lot of money

01:21:08.901 --> 01:21:11.020
to get certain spectrum.

01:21:11.020 --> 01:21:13.350
So suppose you had this problem.

01:21:13.350 --> 01:21:17.205
Here's tower A, this is A's
range, where it reaches.

01:21:17.205 --> 01:21:20.750
Here's tower B, so
it overlaps some

01:21:20.750 --> 01:21:36.660
with A. Here's tower C. Here's
tower E. And here's tower D.

01:21:36.660 --> 01:21:38.280
All right now the
question would be,

01:21:38.280 --> 01:21:40.869
how many radio
frequencies do you need?

01:21:40.869 --> 01:21:42.910
What's the minimum number
of frequencies you need

01:21:42.910 --> 01:21:45.916
to enable all the towers here?

01:21:45.916 --> 01:21:47.480
We could make that be a graph.

01:21:47.480 --> 01:21:49.760
There's a node for each tower.

01:21:49.760 --> 01:21:54.400
And an edge between
towers, if they overlap.

01:21:54.400 --> 01:21:58.650
C doesn't overlap
with B, E does.

01:21:58.650 --> 01:22:00.970
E overlaps here.

01:22:00.970 --> 01:22:05.060
And then D overlaps here.

01:22:05.060 --> 01:22:09.197
So how many frequencies do
you need for this graph?

01:22:09.197 --> 01:22:10.360
AUDIENCE: Four.

01:22:10.360 --> 01:22:14.580
PROFESSOR: Four would
work, three is better.

01:22:14.580 --> 01:22:16.512
Can you do two?

01:22:19.900 --> 01:22:22.380
No you can't do two,
because you got here.

01:22:22.380 --> 01:22:23.820
But you could do three.

01:22:23.820 --> 01:22:29.830
You could do one,
two, three, two, one.

01:22:29.830 --> 01:22:30.841
This problem comes up--

01:22:30.841 --> 01:22:31.715
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:22:31.715 --> 01:22:33.010
PROFESSOR: Did I screw up?

01:22:33.010 --> 01:22:34.660
Ooh, no I can't do that.

01:22:34.660 --> 01:22:36.630
One, two, yeah much better.

01:22:36.630 --> 01:22:39.300
All right, this problem
comes up all over the place.

01:22:39.300 --> 01:22:41.640
I'm certain you'll see it
sometime in your career,

01:22:41.640 --> 01:22:44.015
you'll have some problem, or
you're scheduling something,

01:22:44.015 --> 01:22:45.960
and it's really a graph
problem in disguise.

01:22:45.960 --> 01:22:48.250
OK that's it for today.

